HOW IT WORKS

The ESP8266 connects to your PC via WiFi. Your PC runs a small Python script that reads system stats using LibreHardwareMonitor.
These stats include CPU, GPU, RAM, VRAM, storage, upload and download speeds.
Every second, the Python script sends this data as a simple text packet over WiFi to the
ESP8266's IP address. The ESP8266 receives the packet and displays the numbers on the 1.8 inch TFT screen.
The 1.3 inch OLED runs a stopwatch independently. No PC data needed. The ESP8266 handles timing internally using millis() function.
Both displays run simultaneously because they use different communication protocols. 
TFT uses SPI. OLED uses I2C. No pin conflicts. No data collisions. Two displays, one microcontroller, zero lag.
